70":"1395–1470","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","December 1445":"December 1445","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1425":"1425","abt 1445":"1445","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","Abt 1430":"about 1430","1453":"1453","about 1445":"about 1445","about 1453":"about 1453","1508":"1508","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Dunkenhaigh Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Clayton Le Moors, Lancashire, England":"Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Dunkenhalgh, Lancashire, England":"Dunkenhalgh, Lancashire, England","Rishton Gt. Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rishton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rushton  . Early bearers: Aleander Rishton, 1560 in   IGI   (Great Harwood, Lancs); Anna Rishton, 1598, Elizabeth Rushton, 1635 in   IGI   (Altham, Lancs); Robert Rishton, 1603, James Rushton, 1627, Robert Riston, 1757 in   IGI   (Colne, Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rushton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rishton (Lancashire) and Rushton (Staffordshire), and perhaps also from Rushton (Cheshire, Northamptonshire), Rushton in East Stoke (Dorset), and Rhiston (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>risc</i> ‘rush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["1  English: (i) perhaps a variant of   Garth   with loss of  <i>-r-</i> before the final consonant. Compare Thomas Gath, 1600, John Garth, 1619 in   IGI   (Saint Keyne, Cornwall); Nicholas Gath, 1716, Thomas Garth, 1726 in   IGI   (Saint Breward, Cornwall). (ii) alternatively, a variant of   Goth   with unrounding of the vowel, if not vice versa.","2  Irish: from  <b>Mag Eochadha</b>,  see  McGough  ."]},{"name":"Riston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Rishton was born in 1425, in Rishton, Lancashire, England, his father, Richard Rishton, was 30 and his mother, Margaret DeHolt, was 25. He married Agnes Sherburne in 1445, in Rishton, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1490, in Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1425–1490":"1425–1490","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1425–